ely.\n\nExamining the code more carefully, the content is definitely being read from disk as a separate operation, so the bug must be elsewhere—maybe the wrong endpoint is being called, or there's an issue with how the data is being returned to the frontend.\n\nLooking at the git log command, I see it skips files with no git history entirely, which means new untracked files won't show up in the prompt files list at all. But that's a different issue from what we're seeing. Even if the git command succeeds and the file read fails, we'd get history populated with empty content, which would still require two clicks to see the commits. Let me reconsider the actual problem here.\n\nThe API returns `prompt_files` with `path`, `content`, and `history` for each file. The JavaScript renders each one as a collapsible section showing the file path, then the content if it exists, or \"No content\" if it doesn't, and then a nested collapsible for the history. So the bug must be in how the content is being populated or displayed versus the history.\n\nLet me look at the handler more carefully to see if the `content` field is somehow getting populated with git log output instead of the actual file contents...\n\nExamining the git command...\n\nActually, I'm realizing the scoping is correct here - the `content` variable gets the file data separately from the `history` which comes from parsing the git log output. They're being handled independently, so the file content shouldn't be getting mixed up with commit information.\n\nLet me look at what actually changed in the handler.go file to see if the issue is somewhere else entirely.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":22915,"cache_read_input_tokens":16521,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":22915,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id